Section 1: Dataset Description¶

The final dataset, df, that I have constructed for the development of the desired web app is shown below, along with the presentation of data cleaning and transformation. Explanations for each step of the manipulation is provided in comments.

import pandas as pd

#import data
gpa_raw = pd.read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/wadefagen/datasets/master/gpa/uiuc-gpa-dataset.csv')

#add two new columns: quality points and class size
gpa_raw['quality points'] = gpa_raw['A+']*4 + gpa_raw['A']*4 + gpa_raw['A-']*3.67 + gpa_raw['B+']*3.33 + gpa_raw['B']*3 + gpa_raw['B-']*2.67 + gpa_raw['C+']*2.33+ gpa_raw['C']*2 + gpa_raw['C-']*1.67 + gpa_raw['D+']*1.33 + gpa_raw['D']*1 + gpa_raw['D-']*0.67
gpa_raw['class size'] = gpa_raw['A+'] + gpa_raw['A'] + gpa_raw['A-'] + gpa_raw['B+'] + gpa_raw['B'] + gpa_raw['B-'] + gpa_raw['C+'] + gpa_raw['C'] + gpa_raw['C-'] + gpa_raw['D+'] + gpa_raw['D'] + gpa_raw['D-'] + gpa_raw['F'] + gpa_raw['W']

#Use Groupby mechanics to calculate gpa by class 
quality_points_sum = gpa_raw['quality points'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum()
class_size_sum = gpa_raw['class size'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum()
gpa_by_instructor = quality_points_sum/class_size_sum

#gbi_df presents gpa by class
gbi_df = gpa_by_instructor.reset_index()
gbi_df = gbi_df.rename(columns = {0:"GPA"})

#add number of students, Students, column to gbi_df
student_sum = class_size_sum.reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, student_sum)
gbi_df = gbi_df.rename(columns = {"class size":"Students"})

#add frequencies of each grade to gbi_df
ap_sum = gpa_raw['A+'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, ap_sum)
a_sum = gpa_raw['A'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, a_sum)
am_sum = gpa_raw['A-'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, am_sum)
bp_sum = gpa_raw['B+'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, bp_sum)
b_sum = gpa_raw['B'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, b_sum)
bm_sum = gpa_raw['B-'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, bm_sum)
cp_sum = gpa_raw['C+'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, cp_sum)
c_sum = gpa_raw['C'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, c_sum)
cm_sum = gpa_raw['C-'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, cm_sum)
dp_sum = gpa_raw['D+'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, dp_sum)
d_sum = gpa_raw['D'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, d_sum)
dm_sum = gpa_raw['D-'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, dm_sum)
f_sum = gpa_raw['F'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, f_sum)
w_sum = gpa_raw['W'].groupby([gpa_raw['Primary Instructor'], gpa_raw['Course Title']]).sum().reset_index()
gbi_df = pd.merge(gbi_df, w_sum)

#remove unnecessary columns from gpa_raw
gpa_raw_filtered = gpa_raw.drop(['Year','Term','YearTerm','A+','A','A-','B+','B','B-','C+','C','C-','D+','D','D-','F','W','quality points','class size'],axis=1)

#merge gbi_df and gpa_raw
df = pd.merge(gbi_df, gpa_raw_filtered, how='left').drop_duplicates(subset=['Course Title', 'Primary Instructor'])
df = df.sort_values(by=['Subject','Number'])

#move columns, Subject and Number, to the front
subject_column = df['Subject']
df.drop(labels=['Subject'], axis=1, inplace = True)
df.insert(0, 'Subject', subject_column)
number_column = df['Number']
df.drop(labels=['Number'], axis=1, inplace = True)
df.insert(1, 'Number', number_column)
df = df.reset_index(drop=True)

In addition to course subjects (Subject), course numbers (Number), instructors who have taught the section (Primary Instructor), and course title (Course Title), the final dataset includes a calculation of overall grades (GPA), number of students for each letter grade (A+, A, ...W), and number of students that attended each section (Students) for each of the instructor's accumulated offerings of every class presented in the raw dataset. Groupby mechanics was used to expedite the process.

Section 2: Question of Interest¶

The goal of my web app is plain and simple: to provide a good visualization of grade difference between different sections of a selected course.

I must admit that the provided example, Grade Disparity between sections at UIUC by Wade Fagen-Ulmschneider, has been crafted to near perfection by professor Wade and his team. However, I would like to make a bold claim that my web app can be easier on the eyes to some users. Instead of selecting only the course subject and having to drag down to whichever specific course number the user is looking for, my web app allows the user to select both course subject and number in dropdown. Once those two options are selected, the bar chart for the selected course appears subsequently in the middle of the screen. I also addded the number of students for each letter grade to the chart, where if the user hovers on the bar the data are displayed along with other information.

Section 3: Testing of the Web App¶

In order to test the web app, I chose three different classes to check if the filtered dataframe from the raw dataset for each of the chosen classes matches the information provided in the web app. To be specific, I filtered the raw dataset to a specific section of a course and calculated the gpa across all offerings of the section and the sum of the number of students who have taken the section.

Below are the codes. Each set of codes is followed by the screenshot of the test case.

Section 4: Conclusion & Discussion¶

What I believe I did well in this project is that I was able to construct a solid and clean final dataset that has all the information needed and unnecessary variables taken out. It was a time-consuming process, but it was worth the effort. Also, my visualization provides a straightforward look that is of no difficulty to the users. Colored bar charts give the clearest and easiest visualization for the job, and users can easily tell the difference in grades and the number of students between different sections of the course. This excellently meets the goal I described in section 2, to provide a good visualization of grade differences between different sections of a selected course. Visualizing the number of students

There are improvements that can be made from my web app, though. Some useful statistics, such as median, average GPA of the course across all offered sections, percentage of students for each letter grade, etc. would make my web app more attractive. If someone is to continue working on my project, those would be the things they should tackle next.
